	  <title>Example of a Rotation of the Plane</title>
	  <caption>Rotation of the Plane</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Find the matrix representing the counterclockwise rotation of the plane about the origin through the angle of <math>
                  <latex>60</latex>
               </math> degrees.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The specified rotation transformation has <math>
                        <latex>\theta = \tfrac{\pi}{3}</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore it rotates</para.body>
               </para>
			            <ul>
				              <li>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>the vector <math>
                              <latex>\StdBss{1}=(1,0)</latex>
                           </math> into the vector <math>
                              <latex>(\cos\theta , \sin\theta) = (\tfrac{1}{2} , \tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2})</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </li>
				              <li>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>the vector <math>
                              <latex>\StdBss{2}=(0,1)</latex>
                           </math> into the vector <math>
                              <latex>(-\sin\theta , \cos\theta) = (-\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\tfrac{1}{2})</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </li>
			            </ul>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>These vectors form the columns of the rotation matrix:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
R_{\pi/3} := 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
\tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} &amp; \tfrac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right]\ =\ \dfrac{1}{2}\,
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
1 &amp; -\sqrt{3} \\
\sqrt{3} &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This means that a point <math>
                        <latex>(x,y)\in\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> gets transformed into the point</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
R_{\pi/3}(x,y) = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
\tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} &amp; \tfrac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{r} x \\ y \end{array}
\right] = \dfrac{1}{2}\cdot
\left[
\begin{array}{r} x - \sqrt{3}\, y \\ \sqrt{3}\, x + y \end{array}
\right]
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
